data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods** (since `Span<T>` is a ref struct), so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable` overload by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option A: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option B: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Either approach ensures the expression tree uses the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays, which now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`.
